</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The liver has a complex vascular supply, which involves the inflow of oxygenated blood through the hepatic artery (systemic circulation) and deoxygenated blood through the portal vein (portal circulation), as well as the outflow of deoxygenated blood through the hepatic veins to the inferior vena cava. A spectrum of vascular variants can involve the liver. Some of these variants may result in areas of enhancement that can mimic more serious pathologic conditions. In this article, the authors discuss a spectrum of variants and pathologic conditions that may involve the liver vasculature. These include variants, anomalies, and diseases involving the portal vein, such as rudimentary portal vein, thrombosis, cavernous transformation, thrombotic angiitis, thrombophlebitis, transient hepatic attenuation difference or transient hepatic intensity difference, portal venous aneurysm, and portal vein gas. The hepatic artery can be involved by various diseases, including thrombosis, stenosis, and aneurysm or pseudoaneurysm. Unusual “third inflow” sources of venous inflow are also discussed, including aberrant right gastric vein, aberrant left gastric vein, epigastric-paraumbilical veins, and cholecystic vein. A spectrum of variants and diseases involving the inferior vena cava and hepatic veins, including thrombosis, Budd-Chiari syndrome, veno-occlusive disease, stenosis, torsion, congestive hepatopathy, and peliosis hepatis, are discussed. Vascular shunts are illustrated, including portosystemic shunts (intra- and extrahepatic), arterioportal shunt, shunts of hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia, and acquired arteriovenous fistula. Familiarity with the pathogenesis and imaging features of these vascular entities can aid radiologic diagnoses and guide appropriate patient management.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160161">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160161">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig1.jpeg" height="1848" width="2300" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Drawing shows magnified cross section of the liver demonstrating hepatic lobules, which are hexagonal and represent the small microscopic units of the liver. The smallest portal vein (<i>PV</i>), hepatic artery (<i>HA</i>), and bile duct (<i>BD</i>) branches are located at the corners of the hepatic lobules. Central veins are located at the center of each lobule and drain to the hepatic veins, then the inferior vena cava (IVC).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig2a.jpeg" height="1295" width="1669" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Anatomic variants of the portal vein. Axial oblique maximum intensity projection contrast-enhanced magnetic resonance (MR) images demonstrate the most common anatomic variations of the portovenous system. <i>LPV</i> = left portal vein, <i>MPV</i> = mesoportal vein, <i>RAPV</i> = right anterior portal vein, <i>RPPV</i> = right posterior portal vein, <i>RPV</i> = right portal vein. <b>(a)</b> Type I is the standard branching pattern of the portal vein. <b>(b)</b> Type II is trifurcation of the main portal vein, which divides into right anterior, right posterior, and left portal vein branches. <b>(c)</b> In type III, the RPPV is the first branch of the main portal vein and the LPV is the final branch, arising from the RAPV. <b>(d)</b> In type IV, a segment VII branch arises from the RPV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig2b.jpeg" height="1295" width="1681" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Anatomic variants of the portal vein. Axial oblique maximum intensity projection contrast-enhanced magnetic resonance (MR) images demonstrate the most common anatomic variations of the portovenous system. <i>LPV</i> = left portal vein, <i>MPV</i> = mesoportal vein, <i>RAPV</i> = right anterior portal vein, <i>RPPV</i> = right posterior portal vein, <i>RPV</i> = right portal vein. <b>(a)</b> Type I is the standard branching pattern of the portal vein. <b>(b)</b> Type II is trifurcation of the main portal vein, which divides into right anterior, right posterior, and left portal vein branches. <b>(c)</b> In type III, the RPPV is the first branch of the main portal vein and the LPV is the final branch, arising from the RAPV. <b>(d)</b> In type IV, a segment VII branch arises from the RPV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig2c.jpeg" height="1289" width="1669" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Anatomic variants of the portal vein. Axial oblique maximum intensity projection contrast-enhanced magnetic resonance (MR) images demonstrate the most common anatomic variations of the portovenous system. <i>LPV</i> = left portal vein, <i>MPV</i> = mesoportal vein, <i>RAPV</i> = right anterior portal vein, <i>RPPV</i> = right posterior portal vein, <i>RPV</i> = right portal vein. <b>(a)</b> Type I is the standard branching pattern of the portal vein. <b>(b)</b> Type II is trifurcation of the main portal vein, which divides into right anterior, right posterior, and left portal vein branches. <b>(c)</b> In type III, the RPPV is the first branch of the main portal vein and the LPV is the final branch, arising from the RAPV. <b>(d)</b> In type IV, a segment VII branch arises from the RPV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig2d.jpeg" height="1289" width="1681" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span>. Anatomic variants of the portal vein. Axial oblique maximum intensity projection contrast-enhanced magnetic resonance (MR) images demonstrate the most common anatomic variations of the portovenous system. <i>LPV</i> = left portal vein, <i>MPV</i> = mesoportal vein, <i>RAPV</i> = right anterior portal vein, <i>RPPV</i> = right posterior portal vein, <i>RPV</i> = right portal vein. <b>(a)</b> Type I is the standard branching pattern of the portal vein. <b>(b)</b> Type II is trifurcation of the main portal vein, which divides into right anterior, right posterior, and left portal vein branches. <b>(c)</b> In type III, the RPPV is the first branch of the main portal vein and the LPV is the final branch, arising from the RAPV. <b>(d)</b> In type IV, a segment VII branch arises from the RPV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig3a.jpeg" height="1317" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Rudimentary left portal vein with left hepatic lobe atrophy in a 32-year-old woman who was found to have splenomegaly at ultrasonography (US). Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images demonstrate a normal right portal vein (white arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), hypoplastic left hepatic lobe (white arrow in <b>b</b>), and small (rudimentary) left portal vein (black arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig3b.jpeg" height="1332" width="1829" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Rudimentary left portal vein with left hepatic lobe atrophy in a 32-year-old woman who was found to have splenomegaly at ultrasonography (US). Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images demonstrate a normal right portal vein (white arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), hypoplastic left hepatic lobe (white arrow in <b>b</b>), and small (rudimentary) left portal vein (black arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig3c.jpeg" height="1332" width="1721" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Rudimentary left portal vein with left hepatic lobe atrophy in a 32-year-old woman who was found to have splenomegaly at ultrasonography (US). Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images demonstrate a normal right portal vein (white arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), hypoplastic left hepatic lobe (white arrow in <b>b</b>), and small (rudimentary) left portal vein (black arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig4a.jpeg" height="1284" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Tumor thrombus of the portal vein in a 58-year-old man with hepatocellular carcinoma. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR images in arterial <b>(a)</b> and venous <b>(b)</b> phases and T2-weighted image <b>(c)</b> demonstrate an infiltrative hepatocellular carcinoma involving the left hepatic lobe, with a tumor thrombus (arrows) mainly within the left portal vein and proximal right portal vein exhibiting enhancement in the arterial phase and washout in the venous phase, similar to the tumor, with mild increased signal intensity on the T2-weighted image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig4b.jpeg" height="1244" width="1739" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Tumor thrombus of the portal vein in a 58-year-old man with hepatocellular carcinoma. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR images in arterial <b>(a)</b> and venous <b>(b)</b> phases and T2-weighted image <b>(c)</b> demonstrate an infiltrative hepatocellular carcinoma involving the left hepatic lobe, with a tumor thrombus (arrows) mainly within the left portal vein and proximal right portal vein exhibiting enhancement in the arterial phase and washout in the venous phase, similar to the tumor, with mild increased signal intensity on the T2-weighted image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig4c.jpeg" height="1244" width="1811" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Tumor thrombus of the portal vein in a 58-year-old man with hepatocellular carcinoma. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR images in arterial <b>(a)</b> and venous <b>(b)</b> phases and T2-weighted image <b>(c)</b> demonstrate an infiltrative hepatocellular carcinoma involving the left hepatic lobe, with a tumor thrombus (arrows) mainly within the left portal vein and proximal right portal vein exhibiting enhancement in the arterial phase and washout in the venous phase, similar to the tumor, with mild increased signal intensity on the T2-weighted image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig5a.jpeg" height="1362" width="1566" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Cavernous transformation of the portal vein in a 59-year-old man with a history of cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler image demonstrates multiple vessels with aliasing (arrows) at the liver hilum. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates multiple dilated collaterals (arrow) in the liver hilum without visualization of the main portal vein, due to cavernous transformation secondary to portal vein thrombosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig5b.jpeg" height="1362" width="1784" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Cavernous transformation of the portal vein in a 59-year-old man with a history of cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler image demonstrates multiple vessels with aliasing (arrows) at the liver hilum. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates multiple dilated collaterals (arrow) in the liver hilum without visualization of the main portal vein, due to cavernous transformation secondary to portal vein thrombosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig6a.jpeg" height="1376" width="1778" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Thrombotic angiitis in a 29-year-old woman with a history of systemic lupus erythematosus. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted half-Fourier RARE (rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement) image shows halos (arrows) of high signal intensity surrounding the portal vein branches in the left lobe. <b>(b)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted image during the arterial phase shows left lobe transient hepatic intensity difference (<abbr title="transient hepatic intensity difference">THID</abbr>) together with foci of low signal intensity with peripheral enhancement (arrow). Biopsy showed sterile abscesses. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted images during the portovenous <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> phases show occlusion of the portovenous branch (arrow in <b>c</b>) with periportal enhancement in the delayed phase (arrow in <b>d</b>). At follow-up after treatment with steroids, the portal vein reopened and the enhancement and parenchymal changes completely resolved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig6b.jpeg" height="1376" width="1772" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Thrombotic angiitis in a 29-year-old woman with a history of systemic lupus erythematosus. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted half-Fourier RARE (rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement) image shows halos (arrows) of high signal intensity surrounding the portal vein branches in the left lobe. <b>(b)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted image during the arterial phase shows left lobe transient hepatic intensity difference (<abbr title="transient hepatic intensity difference">THID</abbr>) together with foci of low signal intensity with peripheral enhancement (arrow). Biopsy showed sterile abscesses. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted images during the portovenous <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> phases show occlusion of the portovenous branch (arrow in <b>c</b>) with periportal enhancement in the delayed phase (arrow in <b>d</b>). At follow-up after treatment with steroids, the portal vein reopened and the enhancement and parenchymal changes completely resolved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig6c.jpeg" height="1374" width="1772" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Thrombotic angiitis in a 29-year-old woman with a history of systemic lupus erythematosus. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted half-Fourier RARE (rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement) image shows halos (arrows) of high signal intensity surrounding the portal vein branches in the left lobe. <b>(b)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted image during the arterial phase shows left lobe transient hepatic intensity difference (<abbr title="transient hepatic intensity difference">THID</abbr>) together with foci of low signal intensity with peripheral enhancement (arrow). Biopsy showed sterile abscesses. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted images during the portovenous <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> phases show occlusion of the portovenous branch (arrow in <b>c</b>) with periportal enhancement in the delayed phase (arrow in <b>d</b>). At follow-up after treatment with steroids, the portal vein reopened and the enhancement and parenchymal changes completely resolved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig6d.jpeg" height="1374" width="1778" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span>. Thrombotic angiitis in a 29-year-old woman with a history of systemic lupus erythematosus. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted half-Fourier RARE (rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement) image shows halos (arrows) of high signal intensity surrounding the portal vein branches in the left lobe. <b>(b)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted image during the arterial phase shows left lobe transient hepatic intensity difference (<abbr title="transient hepatic intensity difference">THID</abbr>) together with foci of low signal intensity with peripheral enhancement (arrow). Biopsy showed sterile abscesses. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted images during the portovenous <b>(c)</b> and delayed <b>(d)</b> phases show occlusion of the portovenous branch (arrow in <b>c</b>) with periportal enhancement in the delayed phase (arrow in <b>d</b>). At follow-up after treatment with steroids, the portal vein reopened and the enhancement and parenchymal changes completely resolved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig7a.jpeg" height="1310" width="1777" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Thrombophlebitis in a 62-year-old man with a history of colitis who presented with septic shock. Axial <b>(a–d)</b>, coronal reformatted <b>(e)</b>, and sagittal reformatted <b>(f)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show thrombosis (small black arrows) of the portal vein and its branches, a low-attenuation multiloculated lesion (arrowhead in <b>d</b>, large black arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) with gas foci that proved to be an abscess, as well as extensive thrombosis (white arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) involving the superior mesenteric vein. There is diffuse enhancement of the walls of the thrombosed portal and superior mesenteric veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig7b.jpeg" height="1310" width="1773" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Thrombophlebitis in a 62-year-old man with a history of colitis who presented with septic shock. Axial <b>(a–d)</b>, coronal reformatted <b>(e)</b>, and sagittal reformatted <b>(f)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show thrombosis (small black arrows) of the portal vein and its branches, a low-attenuation multiloculated lesion (arrowhead in <b>d</b>, large black arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) with gas foci that proved to be an abscess, as well as extensive thrombosis (white arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) involving the superior mesenteric vein. There is diffuse enhancement of the walls of the thrombosed portal and superior mesenteric veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig7c.jpeg" height="1324" width="1826" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Thrombophlebitis in a 62-year-old man with a history of colitis who presented with septic shock. Axial <b>(a–d)</b>, coronal reformatted <b>(e)</b>, and sagittal reformatted <b>(f)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show thrombosis (small black arrows) of the portal vein and its branches, a low-attenuation multiloculated lesion (arrowhead in <b>d</b>, large black arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) with gas foci that proved to be an abscess, as well as extensive thrombosis (white arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) involving the superior mesenteric vein. There is diffuse enhancement of the walls of the thrombosed portal and superior mesenteric veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig7d.jpeg" height="1324" width="1724" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Thrombophlebitis in a 62-year-old man with a history of colitis who presented with septic shock. Axial <b>(a–d)</b>, coronal reformatted <b>(e)</b>, and sagittal reformatted <b>(f)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show thrombosis (small black arrows) of the portal vein and its branches, a low-attenuation multiloculated lesion (arrowhead in <b>d</b>, large black arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) with gas foci that proved to be an abscess, as well as extensive thrombosis (white arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) involving the superior mesenteric vein. There is diffuse enhancement of the walls of the thrombosed portal and superior mesenteric veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig7e.jpeg" height="1583" width="1302" aria-labelledby="fig7e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7e</span>. Thrombophlebitis in a 62-year-old man with a history of colitis who presented with septic shock. Axial <b>(a–d)</b>, coronal reformatted <b>(e)</b>, and sagittal reformatted <b>(f)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show thrombosis (small black arrows) of the portal vein and its branches, a low-attenuation multiloculated lesion (arrowhead in <b>d</b>, large black arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) with gas foci that proved to be an abscess, as well as extensive thrombosis (white arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) involving the superior mesenteric vein. There is diffuse enhancement of the walls of the thrombosed portal and superior mesenteric veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig7e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig7f.jpeg" height="1583" width="1148" aria-labelledby="fig7f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7f</span>. Thrombophlebitis in a 62-year-old man with a history of colitis who presented with septic shock. Axial <b>(a–d)</b>, coronal reformatted <b>(e)</b>, and sagittal reformatted <b>(f)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show thrombosis (small black arrows) of the portal vein and its branches, a low-attenuation multiloculated lesion (arrowhead in <b>d</b>, large black arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) with gas foci that proved to be an abscess, as well as extensive thrombosis (white arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) involving the superior mesenteric vein. There is diffuse enhancement of the walls of the thrombosed portal and superior mesenteric veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig7f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig8a.jpeg" height="1288" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. <abbr title="transient hepatic intensity difference">THID</abbr> in a 58-year-old man with pancreatic adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted images in the arterial <b>(a)</b> and venous <b>(b)</b> phases demonstrate a wedge-shaped area of hyperenhancement in the arterial phase (black arrow in <b>a</b>), which becomes isointense in the venous phase. An adjacent hypointense lesion (white arrow) was proven to represent metastasis. (c) Drawing shows an occluded portal vein branch secondary to a small mass (large white arrow). The associated hepatic arterial branch (gray arrow) takes over the blood supply of the wedge-shaped peripheral segment (small white arrows), resulting in increased blood flow, which results in <abbr title="transient hepatic attenuation difference">THAD</abbr> or <abbr title="transient hepatic intensity difference">THID</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig8b.jpeg" height="1272" width="1777" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. <abbr title="transient hepatic intensity difference">THID</abbr> in a 58-year-old man with pancreatic adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted images in the arterial <b>(a)</b> and venous <b>(b)</b> phases demonstrate a wedge-shaped area of hyperenhancement in the arterial phase (black arrow in <b>a</b>), which becomes isointense in the venous phase. An adjacent hypointense lesion (white arrow) was proven to represent metastasis. (c) Drawing shows an occluded portal vein branch secondary to a small mass (large white arrow). The associated hepatic arterial branch (gray arrow) takes over the blood supply of the wedge-shaped peripheral segment (small white arrows), resulting in increased blood flow, which results in <abbr title="transient hepatic attenuation difference">THAD</abbr> or <abbr title="transient hepatic intensity difference">THID</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig8c.jpeg" height="1272" width="1573" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. <abbr title="transient hepatic intensity difference">THID</abbr> in a 58-year-old man with pancreatic adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted images in the arterial <b>(a)</b> and venous <b>(b)</b> phases demonstrate a wedge-shaped area of hyperenhancement in the arterial phase (black arrow in <b>a</b>), which becomes isointense in the venous phase. An adjacent hypointense lesion (white arrow) was proven to represent metastasis. (c) Drawing shows an occluded portal vein branch secondary to a small mass (large white arrow). The associated hepatic arterial branch (gray arrow) takes over the blood supply of the wedge-shaped peripheral segment (small white arrows), resulting in increased blood flow, which results in <abbr title="transient hepatic attenuation difference">THAD</abbr> or <abbr title="transient hepatic intensity difference">THID</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig9a.jpeg" height="1365" width="1748" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Portal venous aneurysm in an 85-year-old man with metastatic pancreatic tail carcinoma. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> reformatted contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate a focal saccular aneurysm (arrow) of the extrahepatic portal vein. Incidental note is made of the hypoattenuating lesion at the liver dome representing a treated metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig9b.jpeg" height="1365" width="1601" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Portal venous aneurysm in an 85-year-old man with metastatic pancreatic tail carcinoma. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> reformatted contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate a focal saccular aneurysm (arrow) of the extrahepatic portal vein. Incidental note is made of the hypoattenuating lesion at the liver dome representing a treated metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig10a.jpeg" height="1374" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Portal venous gas in a 55-year-old woman who presented with abdominal pain and was found to be septic. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate pneumatosis intestinalis (intramural air within small bowel loops) due to bowel ischemia (arrows in <b>b</b>), with portal venous air (white arrows in <b>a</b>) and a wedge-shaped area of low attenuation (black arrow in <b>a</b>) consistent with hepatic infarction. Ascites is present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig10b.jpeg" height="1374" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Portal venous gas in a 55-year-old woman who presented with abdominal pain and was found to be septic. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate pneumatosis intestinalis (intramural air within small bowel loops) due to bowel ischemia (arrows in <b>b</b>), with portal venous air (white arrows in <b>a</b>) and a wedge-shaped area of low attenuation (black arrow in <b>a</b>) consistent with hepatic infarction. Ascites is present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig11a.jpeg" height="1316" width="1733" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Acute donor hepatic artery thrombosis in a 66-year-old man with elevated liver function enzymes 5 days after orthotopic liver transplantation (<abbr title="orthotopic liver transplantation">OLT</abbr>). Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered reconstruction MR <b>(b)</b> images demonstrate abrupt occlusion (cutoff) of the common hepatic artery caused by a thrombus (arrow). Surgeons were not able to salvage the hepatic artery and had to perform liver retransplantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig11b.jpeg" height="1316" width="1416" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Acute donor hepatic artery thrombosis in a 66-year-old man with elevated liver function enzymes 5 days after orthotopic liver transplantation (<abbr title="orthotopic liver transplantation">OLT</abbr>). Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered reconstruction MR <b>(b)</b> images demonstrate abrupt occlusion (cutoff) of the common hepatic artery caused by a thrombus (arrow). Surgeons were not able to salvage the hepatic artery and had to perform liver retransplantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig12a.jpeg" height="1311" width="1695" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Hepatic artery stenosis in a 48-year-old man with elevated liver function test results 6 months after <abbr title="orthotopic liver transplantation">OLT</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Color and spectral Doppler image demonstrates a tardus parvus waveform characteristic for hepatic arterial stenosis, with a resistive index of 0.4. <b>(b)</b> Image from digital subtraction angiography demonstrates stenosis (arrow) of the common hepatic artery at the site of anastomosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig12b.jpeg" height="1311" width="1655" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Hepatic artery stenosis in a 48-year-old man with elevated liver function test results 6 months after <abbr title="orthotopic liver transplantation">OLT</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Color and spectral Doppler image demonstrates a tardus parvus waveform characteristic for hepatic arterial stenosis, with a resistive index of 0.4. <b>(b)</b> Image from digital subtraction angiography demonstrates stenosis (arrow) of the common hepatic artery at the site of anastomosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig13a.jpeg" height="1329" width="1715" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Hepatic artery pseudoaneurysm in a 48-year-old man with a history of liver transplantation for hepatocellular carcinoma who presented for posttransplantation follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler image demonstrates multidirectional flow (yin-yang sign) (black arrow) characteristic of pseudoaneurysm, with a partial thrombus (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial oblique contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR angiogram demonstrates focal aneurysmal dilatation (arrow) of the common hepatic artery at the site of anastomosis. The patient subsequently underwent resection of the hepatic artery pseudoaneurysm and reconstruction of the hepatic artery using a reverse saphenous vein graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig13b.jpeg" height="990" width="1635" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Hepatic artery pseudoaneurysm in a 48-year-old man with a history of liver transplantation for hepatocellular carcinoma who presented for posttransplantation follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler image demonstrates multidirectional flow (yin-yang sign) (black arrow) characteristic of pseudoaneurysm, with a partial thrombus (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial oblique contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR angiogram demonstrates focal aneurysmal dilatation (arrow) of the common hepatic artery at the site of anastomosis. The patient subsequently underwent resection of the hepatic artery pseudoaneurysm and reconstruction of the hepatic artery using a reverse saphenous vein graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig14a.jpeg" height="1354" width="1774" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Aberrant right gastric vein. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate a patchy wedge-shaped area of hyperenhancement (black arrows) in segment IV due to a third inflow of blood from the aberrant right gastric vein (white arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig14b.jpeg" height="1354" width="1776" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Aberrant right gastric vein. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate a patchy wedge-shaped area of hyperenhancement (black arrows) in segment IV due to a third inflow of blood from the aberrant right gastric vein (white arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig15.jpeg" height="1394" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Aberrant left gastric vein in a 32-year-old man with lymphoma who presented for staging. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates a patchy wedge-shaped area of hyperenhancement in segments II and III (black arrow) due to inflow of blood from the aberrant left gastric vein (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig16a.jpeg" height="1374" width="1773" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Hot quadrate sign in a 73-year-old man with a history of lung carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates a wedge-shaped area of enhancement within segment IV (black arrow) with multiple dilated collaterals in the anterior abdominal and chest wall (white arrows), secondary to SVC occlusion. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in a different patient demonstrates occlusion of the SVC by a large mass (black arrow), with multiple dilated collaterals of the anterior chest wall (white arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig16b.jpeg" height="1374" width="1777" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Hot quadrate sign in a 73-year-old man with a history of lung carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates a wedge-shaped area of enhancement within segment IV (black arrow) with multiple dilated collaterals in the anterior abdominal and chest wall (white arrows), secondary to SVC occlusion. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in a different patient demonstrates occlusion of the SVC by a large mass (black arrow), with multiple dilated collaterals of the anterior chest wall (white arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig17a.jpeg" height="1296" width="1677" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. BCS in a 30-year-old woman taking oral contraceptive pills who presented with upper abdominal pain. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted image <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced image CT <b>(b)</b> demonstrate an enlarged hepatic caudate lobe with peripheral parenchymal hypoenhancement (arrows in <b>a</b>) and narrowing of the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> by the enlarged caudate lobe (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig17b.jpeg" height="1296" width="1673" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. BCS in a 30-year-old woman taking oral contraceptive pills who presented with upper abdominal pain. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted image <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced image CT <b>(b)</b> demonstrate an enlarged hepatic caudate lobe with peripheral parenchymal hypoenhancement (arrows in <b>a</b>) and narrowing of the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> by the enlarged caudate lobe (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig18a.jpeg" height="1376" width="1774" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Sinusoidal obstructive syndrome in a 47-year-old man with elevated liver function enzymes 54 days after stem cell transplantation for myelodysplastic syndrome. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images at different levels demonstrate significantly heterogeneous enhancement of liver parenchyma, significant thickening (arrow in <b>b</b>) of the gallbladder wall, and ascites.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig18b.jpeg" height="1376" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Sinusoidal obstructive syndrome in a 47-year-old man with elevated liver function enzymes 54 days after stem cell transplantation for myelodysplastic syndrome. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images at different levels demonstrate significantly heterogeneous enhancement of liver parenchyma, significant thickening (arrow in <b>b</b>) of the gallbladder wall, and ascites.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig19a.jpeg" height="1114" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Peliosis hepatis in a 47-year-old woman with human immunodeficiency virus infection who presented with elevated liver function enzymes and an indeterminate lesion (not shown) at US. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted image demonstrates a well-circumscribed lesion (arrow) in segment VII. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted images in the arterial <b>(b)</b> and delayed <b>(c)</b> phases demonstrate early peripheral enhancement (arrow in <b>b</b>) with homogeneous enhancement (arrow in <b>c</b>) in the delayed phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig19b.jpeg" height="1099" width="1774" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Peliosis hepatis in a 47-year-old woman with human immunodeficiency virus infection who presented with elevated liver function enzymes and an indeterminate lesion (not shown) at US. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted image demonstrates a well-circumscribed lesion (arrow) in segment VII. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted images in the arterial <b>(b)</b> and delayed <b>(c)</b> phases demonstrate early peripheral enhancement (arrow in <b>b</b>) with homogeneous enhancement (arrow in <b>c</b>) in the delayed phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig19c.jpeg" height="1099" width="1776" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span>. Peliosis hepatis in a 47-year-old woman with human immunodeficiency virus infection who presented with elevated liver function enzymes and an indeterminate lesion (not shown) at US. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted image demonstrates a well-circumscribed lesion (arrow) in segment VII. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted images in the arterial <b>(b)</b> and delayed <b>(c)</b> phases demonstrate early peripheral enhancement (arrow in <b>b</b>) with homogeneous enhancement (arrow in <b>c</b>) in the delayed phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig20a.jpeg" height="1375" width="1774" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Passive hepatic congestion secondary to congestive heart failure in a 49-year-old woman with cardiomyopathy. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images in the arterial <b>(a)</b> and venous <b>(b)</b> phases demonstrate significantly heterogeneous enhancement of the liver with reticular areas of hypoattenuation and markedly dilated hepatic veins (arrows in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig20b.jpeg" height="1375" width="1776" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Passive hepatic congestion secondary to congestive heart failure in a 49-year-old woman with cardiomyopathy. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images in the arterial <b>(a)</b> and venous <b>(b)</b> phases demonstrate significantly heterogeneous enhancement of the liver with reticular areas of hypoattenuation and markedly dilated hepatic veins (arrows in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig21.jpeg" height="1734" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> torsion in a 55-year-old man after liver transplantation. Inferior venacavogram demonstrates a ribbonlike narrowing (arrow) of the suprahepatic <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>, representing torsion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig22a.jpeg" height="1564" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Arterioportal shunt secondary to hepatocellular carcinoma in a 62-year-old man with a history of cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler image demonstrates a small hypoechoic focal lesion (white arrow) consistent with hepatocellular carcinoma, with an adjacent area of aliasing consistent with an arterioportal shunt (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates an enhancing lesion (white arrow) consistent with hepatocellular carcinoma, with an adjacent small arterioportal shunt (black arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal reformatted image demonstrates early filling (arrow) of the portal vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig22b.jpeg" height="1349" width="1743" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Arterioportal shunt secondary to hepatocellular carcinoma in a 62-year-old man with a history of cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler image demonstrates a small hypoechoic focal lesion (white arrow) consistent with hepatocellular carcinoma, with an adjacent area of aliasing consistent with an arterioportal shunt (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates an enhancing lesion (white arrow) consistent with hepatocellular carcinoma, with an adjacent small arterioportal shunt (black arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal reformatted image demonstrates early filling (arrow) of the portal vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig22c.jpeg" height="1349" width="1407" aria-labelledby="fig22c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22c</span>. Arterioportal shunt secondary to hepatocellular carcinoma in a 62-year-old man with a history of cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler image demonstrates a small hypoechoic focal lesion (white arrow) consistent with hepatocellular carcinoma, with an adjacent area of aliasing consistent with an arterioportal shunt (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates an enhancing lesion (white arrow) consistent with hepatocellular carcinoma, with an adjacent small arterioportal shunt (black arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal reformatted image demonstrates early filling (arrow) of the portal vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig22c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig23a.jpeg" height="1373" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. Acquired arterioportal shunt in a 47-year-old man after liver biopsy for persistent elevation of liver enzymes. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images in the arterial phase demonstrate a linear enhancing structure representing an arterioportal fistula (white arrow in <b>a</b>) and a wedge-shaped area of hyperenhancement secondary to <abbr title="transient hepatic attenuation difference">THAD</abbr> (black arrow in <b>a</b>), with early filling of the portal vein (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig23b.jpeg" height="1373" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. Acquired arterioportal shunt in a 47-year-old man after liver biopsy for persistent elevation of liver enzymes. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images in the arterial phase demonstrate a linear enhancing structure representing an arterioportal fistula (white arrow in <b>a</b>) and a wedge-shaped area of hyperenhancement secondary to <abbr title="transient hepatic attenuation difference">THAD</abbr> (black arrow in <b>a</b>), with early filling of the portal vein (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig24a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span>. Intrahepatic portosystemic shunt in a 76-year-old woman with no history of cirrhosis or distant history of trauma or biopsy. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate a tuft (black arrow) of enhancing vascular channels and both the portal feeding vein (white arrow in <b>b</b>) and the draining hepatic vein (arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig24b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span>. Intrahepatic portosystemic shunt in a 76-year-old woman with no history of cirrhosis or distant history of trauma or biopsy. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate a tuft (black arrow) of enhancing vascular channels and both the portal feeding vein (white arrow in <b>b</b>) and the draining hepatic vein (arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig25a.jpeg" height="1394" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig25a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span>. Extrahepatic portosystemic shunt in a 29-year-old man who presented with abdominal pain. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and axial oblique maximum intensity projection <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate the portal vein <i>(PV)</i> ending as an aneurysm in the porta hepatis, which connects with a venous trunk to the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig25b.jpeg" height="1373" width="1774" aria-labelledby="fig25b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span>. Extrahepatic portosystemic shunt in a 29-year-old man who presented with abdominal pain. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and axial oblique maximum intensity projection <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate the portal vein <i>(PV)</i> ending as an aneurysm in the porta hepatis, which connects with a venous trunk to the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig25c.jpeg" height="1373" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig25c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25c</span>. Extrahepatic portosystemic shunt in a 29-year-old man who presented with abdominal pain. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and axial oblique maximum intensity projection <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate the portal vein <i>(PV)</i> ending as an aneurysm in the porta hepatis, which connects with a venous trunk to the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig25c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig26.jpeg" height="1237" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia in a 42-year-old woman. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates multiple enhancing lesions representing telangiectasias and a dilated common hepatic artery (arrow) larger than the portal vein, a feature described as demonstrative of hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160161/asset/images/large/rg.2017160161.fig27.jpeg" height="3411" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span>. Approach to attenuation/intensity abnormalities at contrast-enhanced CT and MR imaging. <i>ALGVD</i> = aberrant left gastric vein drainage, <i>ARGVD</i> = aberrant right gastric vein drainage, <i>AV</i> = arteriovenous, <i>AVM</i> = arteriovenous malformation, <i>GVHD</i> = graft-versus-host disease, <i>HHT</i> = hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia, <i>PV</i> = portal vein, <i>SOS</i> = sinusoidal obstruction syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160161&